# Proposed Update — code-validity-review.md (or sibling reviewer skill)

**Source:** SkillTest R1.C case-overclaim evaluation of nature-polishing.
**Status:** Draft only. Do not apply to
`/Users/mjm/MinionsOS/minions/roles/reviewer/skills/code-validity-review.md`
(or the appropriate sibling skill) until the user explicitly approves the
R1 synthesis port plan. The exact target file is up to the user — this
proposal lists candidates.

## Target file (user decides)

The boundary-specificity rule applies to *prose criticism quality*, not
specifically to code-validity review. Candidate target files in
`minions/roles/reviewer/skills/`:

- `aspect-note.md` — covers per-aspect criticism format
- `code-validity-review.md` — currently scoped to experiments / reproducibility
- A new file `criticism-quality.md` — if the rule is general enough to
  warrant its own skill

**Recommendation:** add to `aspect-note.md` if the user prefers a single
quality-of-criticism rule; create `criticism-quality.md` if the user
prefers a dedicated skill.

## What to add

### Rule: Name the specific missing experiment, not the design class

Add as a hard rule for any reviewer-side criticism that flags missing
evidence:

> **When criticising a Discussion / clinical-implication / mechanism claim
> for missing evidence, name the SPECIFIC missing experiment, not the
> experimental design class.**
>
> Example (weak): "The data are observational and cannot establish
> causation."
>
> Example (strong): "The study is observational and does not include
> bacterial transfer experiments to germ-free recipients (or equivalent
> intervention design); this experiment would be required to establish
> the protective effect."
>
> The strong form is reviewer-proof: the author either runs the named
> experiment or accepts the boundary. The weak form invites the author
> to argue about whether observational designs can ever establish anything.

Evidence: SkillTest R1.C case-overclaim. Source claimed "this organism
is protective" from observational microbiome data. Baseline criticism
softened to "do not support a clinical recommendation" (correct but
generic). Candidate criticism named the gap: "did not include transfer
experiments." User-equivalent rubric scored candidate +2 on
claim-evidence completeness because the named experiment is verifiable
and arguable.

### Optional Rule: Tier the limitation by what would close it

For any limitation paragraph in a Discussion section:

> **Each limitation should pair with a concrete next step that would
> close it.** "Larger cohorts are required" alone is throat-clearing.
> "Larger cohorts (n ≥ 200) with a second-site replication and
> matching for the three confounders X / Y / Z would close this gap"
> is actionable.

Evidence: same case. Candidate explicitly named "prospective and
mechanistic studies" rather than "future studies will address this."

## What to leave unchanged

The existing reviewer-skill pass structure (Pass A independent →
Pass B history → Pass C consolidation) is unaffected by this rule.
The boundary-specificity rule applies inside any single criticism note,
not to pass orchestration.

## Why this is a single-rule update

R1.C had only one case where this rule fired (case-overclaim, +4 → bucket
Calibrates). A single-case update is generally not enough evidence for
a port; this rule survives because:
1. It maps to a well-known reviewer-quality dimension that holds across
   manuscript types (not specific to microbiome / IBD).
2. It compounds with the existing MinionsOS evidence-first EACN
   communication convention (every claim either evidence-backed,
   speculation, or derived).
3. R2 is expected to test `nature-response` which has its own
   reviewer-criticism quality rules — this update should be re-checked
   against R2 evidence before final port.
